To draw a chessboard in LaTeX, you can use the `chessboard` package. Here's an example of how to use it:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}

\begin{chessboard}
  rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR
\end{chessboard}

\end{document}
```

In this example, the FEN notation `rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR` represents the starting position of a chess game. The `chessboard` package will render this FEN notation as a chessboard.

Here's a breakdown of the FEN notation:

* `rnbqkbnr` represents the ranks of the board, from left to right: rooks, knights, bishops, queens, kings, bishops, knights, and rooks.
* `pppppppp` represents the pawns on the second rank.
* `8` represents an empty rank.
* `PPPPPPPP` represents the pawns on the seventh rank, from right to left.

You can replace this FEN notation with any valid FEN string to display a different chessboard state.

Note that you need to have the `chessboard` package installed in your LaTeX distribution. If you don't have it, you can install it using your package manager or by downloading it from CTAN.

